{
    "title": "Biggest US rail union rejects labor deal, sparking holiday strike concerns",
    "news": [
        {
            "id": 0,
            "text": "Members of the largest US rail workers union rejected a proposed deal on Monday \u2013 a move that sparked concerns of a potential strike just ahead of the busy holiday season."
        },
        {
            "id": 1,
            "text": "Train conductors represented by the Sheet Metal, Air, Rail and Transportation Workers-Transportation Division, or SMART-TD, narrowly rejected the proposed deal."
        },
        {
            "id": 2,
            "text": "The vote drew record turnout among the union\u2019s membership of more than 28,000 conductors and other workers."
        },
        {
            "id": 3,
            "text": "\u201cSMART-TD members with their votes have spoken, it\u2019s now back to the bargaining table for our operating craft members,\u201d SMART-TD President Jeremy Ferguson said in a statement on the decision."
        },
        {
            "id": 4,
            "text": "\u201cThis can all be settled through negotiations and without a strike."
        },
        {
            "id": 5,
            "text": "A settlement would be in the best interests of the workers, the railroads, shippers and the American people.\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 6,
            "text": "\u201cThe ball is now in the railroads\u2019 court."
        },
        {
            "id": 7,
            "text": "Let\u2019s see what they do."
        },
        {
            "id": 8,
            "text": "They can settle this at the bargaining table,\u201d Ferguson added."
        },
        {
            "id": 9,
            "text": "\u201cBut, the railroad executives who constantly complain about government interference and regularly bad-mouth regulators and Congress now want Congress to do the bargaining for them.\u201d"
        },
        {
            "id": 11,
            "text": "Elsewhere, the second-largest rail union, the Brotherhood of Locomotive Engineers and Trainmen, or BLET, voted to approve the deal."
        },
        {
            "id": 12,
            "text": "Collectively, the two unions represent about half the unionized workforce on freight rails nationwide."
        },
        {
            "id": 13,
            "text": "SMART-TD is one of four freight rail unions that have shot down a White House-brokered labor deal, while eight other unions have approved it."
        },
        {
            "id": 14,
            "text": "Due to a preexisting agreement to honor respective picket lines, all 12 unions must sign off on the deal to prevent a strike before the current status quo agreement expires on Dec. 8."
        },
        {
            "id": 15,
            "text": "The rail industry\u2019s labor unions are pushing for more lenient attendance policies and upgraded sick leave policies to ease pressure on workers."
        },
        {
            "id": 16,
            "text": "Rail companies argue expanded policies would force them to bring on more staffers."
        },
        {
            "id": 18,
            "text": "A special board of arbitrators appointed by President Biden outlined the proposed five-year deal, which includes 24% pay raises and a $5,000 bonus for workers."
        },
        {
            "id": 19,
            "text": "A nationwide rail workers strike could cost the US economy more than $2 billion in lost output per day, according to a September analysis by the Association of American Railroads."
        },
        {
            "id": 20,
            "text": "A strike would impact holiday travel and snarl supply chains across various industries, from manufacturing to retail, ahead of the winter holidays."
        },
        {
            "id": 21,
            "text": "Further supply chain difficulties could exacerbate inflation, which had showed signs of easing in October."
        },
        {
            "id": 22,
            "text": "The Retail Industry Leaders Association said a rail strike \u201cwould cause enormous disruption to the flow of goods nationwide\u201d during the holiday shopping season."
        },
        {
            "id": 23,
            "text": "\u201cFortunately, this year\u2019s holiday gifts have already landed on store shelves."
        },
        {
            "id": 24,
            "text": "But an interruption to rail transportation does pose a significant challenge to getting items like perishable food products and e-commerce shipments delivered on time, and it will undoubtedly add to the inflationary pressures already hitting the U.S. economy,\u201d said Jess Dankert, RILA\u2019s vice president of supply chain."
        }
    ],
